  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Virtues for the People\" published by Leuven University Press in 2011 has a notable scholarly uptake, evidenced by 46 citations, indicating an increasing engagement within the academic community.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Virtues for the People,\" published by Leuven University Press in 2011, has made a significant scholarly impact as indicated by its 46 citations. This level of academic recognition suggests that the concepts explored within the book resonate with ongoing discussions in various disciplines, reflecting its relevance and contribution to the field.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The academic discourse surrounding this work indicates a committed exploration of virtues within social contexts, which may appeal to scholars interested in ethics, philosophy, and social sciences. Despite the lack of citations in public forums like Wikipedia or Reddit, the existing citations illustrate an established scholarly footprint that enhances the book's credibility among researchers and practitioners alike.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Moreover, the evidence of scholarly uptake highlights a growing interest in the themes presented in \"Virtues for the People,\" suggesting that the work is influencing academic narratives and potentially guiding future studies. The contextual foundations laid out in the publication prompt further investigation into how virtues inform social practices, which is vital for both theoretical and practical application in contemporary discourse.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">In conclusion, while public engagement metrics are currently absent, the 46 citations signal a robust scholarly impact and underline the book's significance in contributing to discussions related to virtues in society. Continued engagement from academic communities may further illuminate its relevance and potential for broader societal influence.</p>",
